<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
The stems and leaves of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Retief &amp; A. E. van Wyk in S. Afr. J. Bot. 62 (3): 169 - 172" authorityYear="1996" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum obtusicalyx" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum obtusicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are densely covered with soft, woolly trichomes which makes it similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hilliard &amp; B. L. Burtt, Notes Roy. Bot. Gard. Edinburgh 43 (3): 343" authorityYear="1986" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum alticola" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the two species differ in flower colour and size (deep blue corolla, 4
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm vs. pale blue corolla, 5
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7 mm in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. obtusicalyx" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. obtusicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Retief &amp; A. E. van Wyk in S. Afr. J. Bot. 62 (3): 169 - 172" authorityYear="1996" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum obtusicalyx" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum obtusicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has pale blue flowers with corolla 5-7 mm long whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. austroafricanum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. austroafricanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has bright blue flowers with corolla 2.75-4.25 mm long. The two species also show variation in trichome texture and density, i.e., sparsely hairy with short, stiff hairs on both the stem and leaves in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. austroafricanum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. austroafricanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. densely arranged long, woolly hair on both the stem and leaves in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. obtusicalyx" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. obtusicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
