<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Retief &amp; A. E. van Wyk in S. Afr. J. Bot. 62 (3): 169 - 172" authorityYear="1996" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum obtusicalyx" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="obtusicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum obtusicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to South Africa where it has been recorded from Calvinia, Worcester, and Beaufort West in the Northern and Western Cape Provinces (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Known distribution map of C. obtusicalyx in southern Africa based on the specimens examined." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.193.72270.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/658900" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">16</figureCitation>
), it occurs in mountainous areas, often growing on screes below cliffs.
</paragraph>
